SCENE 8.1 - NIKE - GLOBAL BRAND, LOCAL RELEVANCE

VISUAL: Nike global campaigns montage (video/image recreations). Cricket sponsorship in India visualization. Global athlete montage. Nike product adaptation examples.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
(Female, sophisticated, global perspective)

Now, let's look at two masters of global marketing: Nike and Domino's.

Nike has grown to become one of the most recognized brands on the planet through a combination of global marketing tactics and strategic international sponsorships.

How do they do it?

1. Global Brand Consistency: The Nike swoosh, the 'Just Do It' tagline—these are consistent worldwide.

2. Strategic International Sponsorships: Nike sponsors global superstars like Cristiano Ronaldo, Serena Williams, and LeBron James.

3. Local Adaptation: In India, they sponsor cricket stars and create cricket-specific products. In China, they partner with Chinese athletes. In the Middle East, they design modest sportswear.

The Result: A global brand that feels local.

Nike understood that sports are universal. The feeling of scoring a goal or winning a race is shared across cultures. But the execution requires local adaptation.

VISUAL NOTE: Nike global campaigns montage (video/image recreations). Cricket sponsorship in India visualization. Global athlete montage (video/image). Different sports from different countries.

---
SCENE 8.2 - DOMINO'S - THE ULTIMATE ADAPTER

VISUAL: Domino's menu comparison across countries (side-by-side). India-specific Domino's items (Paneer Tikka pizza, Choco Lava Cake). World map showing adaptation examples.

NARRATOR (V.O.)
(Continuing)

Domino's takes adaptation to another level.

Depending on where you live, Domino's has completely different menu items—toppings, sauces, bread, cheeses—tailored for various global markets.

Examples:

India: Paneer Tikka pizza, Chicken Keema Do Pyaza, Choco Lava Cake.

Asia: Seafood toppings, wasabi mayo, kimchi pizza in Korea.

Middle East: Halal meat, no pork options.

Japan: Teriyaki chicken, squid, mayo-based pizzas.

Brazil: Catupiry cheese, unique local flavors.

The Genius: Domino's standardized their operational system—how they make pizza, deliver it, manage franchises—but completely adapted their product to local tastes.

They understood: People want pizza, but they want it their way.

The Lesson for Marketers: Think global, act local. The same brand, the same operational excellence—but with local flavor that makes customers feel understood.

VISUAL NOTE: Domino's menu comparison across countries (side-by-side). India-specific Domino's items (Paneer Tikka pizza, Choco Lava Cake) - video/image recreations. World map showing adaptation examples with food icons.

